## Why Delegation Needs Contracts

In a multi-agent system, delegation without contracts is a bug waiting to happen. An agent that calls another agent with unvalidated inputs is one schema drift away from a silent failure.

The DCYFR delegation framework addresses this with typed contracts — TypeScript interfaces that define both the input and output shape of every agent handoff.

```typescript
import { delegate } from '@dcyfr/ai';

interface SummarizeInput {
  text: string;
  maxWords: number;
}

interface SummarizeOutput {
  summary: string;
  wordCount: number;
}

const result = await delegate<SummarizeInput, SummarizeOutput>({
  agent: 'summarizer',
  input: { text: articleContent, maxWords: 100 },
});
```

## Approval Gates

Not all delegations should run autonomously. For high-stakes operations, the framework supports approval gates — points where a human must confirm before execution continues.

```typescript
const result = await delegate({
  agent: 'deploy-agent',
  input: { environment: 'production', version: '2026.3.1' },
  requiresApproval: true,
  approvalTimeout: 300_000, // 5 minutes
});
```

## Error Propagation

When a subagent fails, errors bubble up with full context — the delegation chain, the input that caused the failure, and the agent that reported it. This makes debugging multi-agent failures dramatically faster.

## Next Steps

The delegation framework is available as part of `@dcyfr/ai`. See the [snippet library](https://dcyfr.codes) for copy-paste examples.

## The Budget Problem

Every model has a context window. The moment your agent accumulates more tokens than it can fit, you have a choice: truncate, compress, or fail.

Most implementations truncate. The DCYFR approach is to budget proactively.

## The Guard Pattern

```typescript
const CHARS_PER_TOKEN = 4;

export function guardContextBudget(
  items: string[],
  maxTokens: number,
  reserveTokens = 2048,
): string[] {
  const limit = (maxTokens - reserveTokens) * CHARS_PER_TOKEN;
  let total = 0;
  const result: string[] = [];
  for (const item of items) {
    if (total + item.length > limit) break;
    result.push(item);
    total += item.length;
  }
  return result;
}
```

Reserve tokens for the model's response. Fill context greedily until the budget is hit, then stop.

## Semantic Compression

When recency matters but you can't drop old context, compress it. Summarize earlier turns into a compact representation before adding new ones.

This is the core idea behind the working memory pattern in `@dcyfr/ai`: keep the last N full turns, compress the rest into a rolling summary.

## Sliding Window vs. Summary

| Strategy | Pros | Cons |
|----------|------|------|
| Sliding window | Simple, no information loss for recent turns | Drops old context entirely |
| Summary | Preserves intent across long runs | Summary quality depends on compression model |
| Budget guard | Explicit, predictable | Must tune reserve size per model |
